<%= content_for(:title, "Installing the widget") %>

<div class="prose">
  <p>You can embed the Happi widget into your website or web app to allow customers to reach out easily.</p>

  <%= image_tag "docs/widget/example.png", alt: "Happi embedable widget", class: "max-w-sm mx-auto" %>

  <p>You can customise the colours and most of the text within the widget to your liking by passing in options.</p>

  <h3>Using on any webpage</h3>

  <p>Copy the support widget code from your <%= link_to "Widget settings", widget_settings_path, target: "_blank" %>, this is where you will find your publishable key. It should look like the snippet below:</p>

  <pre><code class="text-white">&lt;script src="https://unpkg.com/react@17.0.2/umd/react.production.min.js" type="text/javascript">&lt;/script>
&lt;script src="https://unpkg.com/react-dom@17.0.2/umd/react-dom.production.min.js" type="text/javascript">&lt;/script>
&lt;script src="https://unpkg.com/happi-widget/dist/index.js" type="text/javascript">&lt;/script>
&lt;script type="text/javascript">
  Happi.init({
    publishableKey: "my-publishable-key"
  })
&lt;/script></code></pre>

  <p>Thatâ€™s it, your widget is now installed and should automatically load on your site. If you have users who login to your website or app, you might want to <%= link_to "prefill their customer data", documentation_widget_prefill_data_path %> to save them time and avoid errors.</p>

  <h3>Using with Gatsby/Next.js/React etc</h3>

  <p>First you need to install the `happi-widget` package.</p>


  <pre><code class="text-white">npm i --save happi-widget
<span class="text-gray-500">// or if you use yarn...</span>
yarn add happi-widget</code></pre>

  <pre><code class="text-white">import Happi from "happi-widget"

Happi.init({
  publishableKey: "my-publishable-key"
})</code></pre>
</div>
